Title: Literary Interpretation of the Synoptic Gospels An Introduction to a Course 1 What Interpretation? Which
Author: Philip Fong gospels (Matthew, Mark, Luke) Matt: Blessed 
Note: 2 The Synoptic Gospels  are traditionally referred to as the Synoptic Gospels. Numerous common material: e.g. parable of the sower, the call of Levi, stilling the storm, the transfiguration, Jesus foretelling his passion, and many other. The common passages are all missing from John. Yet, John contains stories/sayings that are completely missing from the three: e.g.  in content: e.g. the parable of the prodigal son is only found in  are the poor in spirit. Luke: Blessed are the poor.  
Date: January 9, 1998  
Abstract: This is a course on studying the gospels. In particular, we will focus on the gospels of Matthew, of Mark, and of Luke. Also, we will learn about the application of literary methods to the interpretation of the mentioned gospels. This is not a course that teaches you how to enrich your devotional experience. Nor is this course a training for leading bible study group. This is a course about vigorously studying the gospels for the simple sake of understanding what God intends us to learn about Him in the gospels. 
